{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/styling-pandas-dataframes-more-than-just-numbers-4bbb790fb919", "time": 1683008932.033035, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/styling-pandas-dataframes-more-than-just-numbers-4bbb790fb919/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Styling Pandas DataFrames: More Than Just Numbers | by Andre Ye | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Styling Pandas DataFrames: More Than Just Numbers", "description": "DataFrames are the most standard method to manipulate and store data in Python \u2014 but did you know that you can store a lot more than just numbers? Pandas has a variety of methods to style your\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://andre-ye.medium.com/membership", "anchor_text": "https://andre-ye.medium.com/membership", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["DataFrames are the most standard method to manipulate and store data in Python \u2014 but did you know that you can store a lot more than just numbers? Pandas has a variety of methods to style your DataFrame, both for the data wrangler\u2019s ease and for those viewing the data.", "To begin, we\u2019ll generate a sample DataFrame. It will have five columns, each with ten rows, all drawn randomly from a normal distribution.", "To color in a DataFrame according to conditional rules, one needs to create a color map. This exists in the form of a function that takes in a value, returning a string \u201ccolor: [color]\u201d. This function colors negative values red. Standard colors are accepted, but hex codes work as well.", "By using the .style.applymap function, the color map is applied to the DataFrame.", "Or for example, say we would like to highlight the maximum value in each column yellow. Like coloring text a certain color, one needs to create a styling function. Because this function highlights the maximum in a series instead of a conditional of every value, this function takes in the complete column (series) and returns a list of styling instructions for each cell in that column.", "In this case, instead of using \u201ccolor: [color]\u201d, background color is done with \u201cbackground-color: [color]\u201d (where, as usual, color can be a standard color name or a hex code).", "Note that because this function applies to each column and not to a value, use not apply_map but apply.", "You may find that applying .style.apply will yield an error if you have already applied something before. This is because using the function creates not a DataFrame but a styled object. To combine many styling elements, use Python method chaining.", "Another method is to simply stack methods on top of each other, such as for example .style.highlight_null().apply().apply_map().", "If you\u2019d like to mark all NaN values, use .style.highlight_null. This can be particularly helpful for making missing values more noticeable.", "To make the DataFrame a heatmap \u2014 that is, values are colored according to their value \u2014 use the .style.background_gradient method. The method takes in a cmap (color map) argument that dictates how it is supposed to be colored. In this case, cmap is created using seaborn\u2019s light_palette, which takes in a root color (in this case, the hex code for blueberry). The cmap argument on line three can also be set to a standard palette name like viridis or magma.", "To set inherent DataFrame properties, use .style.set_properties. This takes in a dictionary as a parameter with the various attributes and their values.", "One can even create \u2018bar charts\u2019 within Pandas DataFrames, in which each bar corresponds with the value of the column. This can be extremely helpful to visualization. In this case, subset refers to the columns that have bars on them.", "You may enjoy some of my other Pandas and Python data science library tutorials.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "ML enthusiast. Join Medium through my referral link: https://andre-ye.medium.com/membership.